Belgacom, Deutsche Bank, Fiat, Henkel: European Equity Preview

-- B y   J e n n i f e r   A .   J o h n s o n
-- 
2011-02-25T05:00:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-24/belgacom-deutsche-bank-fiat-henkel-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index declined 0.6 percent to 280.56.
The Stoxx 50 Index dropped 0.6 percent to 2,667.52. The Euro
Stoxx 50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, fell 0.2
percent to 2,949.13.    Acerinox SA  (ACX SM): The stainless steel producer reported
a profit of 122.7 million euros ($169.2 million), compared with
a net loss of 229.2 million euros a year ago, the company said
in a regulatory filing. The shares fell 0.4 percent to 12.75
euros.  Actividades de Construccion y Servicios SA (ACS SM):
Spain’s biggest builder by revenue said 2010 profit fell 33
percent to 1.31 billion euros after it didn’t repeat one-time
gains. ACS shares gained 0.7 percent to 32.64 euros.  Bekaert NV (BEKB BB): The world’s largest maker of steel
cord used in tires may say second-half net income rose to 181.5
million euros, the average of four analyst estimates compiled by
Bloomberg. Bekaert retreated 0.2 percent to 73.93 euros.    Belgacom SA  (BELG BB): The largest telephone company in
Belgium may say fourth-quarter net income fell to 182.8 million
euros, according to the average of 11 analyst estimates compiled
by Bloomberg. Belgacom rose less than 0.1 percent to 27.25
euros.    Deutsche Bank AG  (DBK GY): Germany’s biggest bank plans to
sell its Frankfurt headquarters to private investors via a fund
held by its DWS unit, Financial Times Deutschland reported,
citing an unidentified person familiar with the process. The
stock declined 0.6 percent to 45.82 euros.    Eiffage SA  (FGR FP): France’s third-largest construction
company estimated sales this year will rise 3 percent to 13.7
billion euros. Eiffage fell 0.8 percent to 40.35 euros.  Fiat SpA (F IM): Standard & Poor’s Ratings Services said it
lowered its long-term corporate credit rating on  Fiat SpA  to BB
from BB+. The outlook is negative, S&P said. The stock rose 0.1
percent to 6.70 euros.  Henkel AG (HEN3 GY): The German maker of Loctite glues and
Persil detergent was downgraded to “hold” from “buy” at
Independent Research GmbH. The shares lost 3.5 percent to 42.62
euros.  Tenaris SpA (TEN IM): The world’s largest maker of seamless
pipes expects large oil producers to increase their investments
this year, Chief Executive Officer Paolo Rocca said in a
conference call. Tenaris eastern hemisphere area manager
Alejandro Lammertyn said the company had “some” delays in
shipments from Egypt. Tenaris fourth-quarter profit rose 44
percent on higher sales. The shares dropped 3.9 percent to 16.34
euros.    Thales SA  (HO FP): Europe’s largest defense-electronics
producer said its net loss shrank to 45 million euros last year
and it expects to “swiftly return to profitability.” Thales
rose 0.2 percent to 26.64 euros.    UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM): Italy’s competition regulator
approved the purchase of UniCredit MedioCredito Centrale SpA by
Poste Italiane, according to a statement posted on the
regulator’s website.  Poste Italiane  is buying 100 percent of the
bank. UniCredit slid 0.5 percent to 1.84 euros.    Valeo SA  (FR FP): France’s second-largest auto-parts
supplier posted a full-year profit on an Asian-led recovery in
auto demand, beating analysts’ expectations and its own
forecasts. Valeo fell 2.8 percent to 40.82 euros.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at 
 nbaker7@bloomberg.net  